Tracking my protein over time

Introduction

Over the past few weeks, I tracked the meals I ate, with a focus on understanding my protein intake. I recorded the timestamp of each meal, whether it was sweet or savoury, if it was self-cooked or not, and how many servings of fruits and vegetables were included. I also calculated the grams of protein in each meal.

This story aims to explore:

Whether cooking my meals led to a higher protein intake.

Whether savoury or sweet meals tended to be higher in protein.

How my protein consumption changed over time.

Cooking and Vegetable Intake

Average Protein by Cooking Method

This bar plot shows that meals cooked by me were more likely to include higher amounts of protein. In contrast, meals I didnt cook tended to have a lower protein content. Cooking at home helped improve the nutritional quality of my meals.

Plot 2

Are Sweet or Savoury Meals Higher in Protein?

This density plot compares the protein content of sweet versus savoury meals. Savoury meals had a noticeably higher average protein level, while sweet meals clustered around the lower end of the protein scale. This shows that sweet meals were generally less nutritious in terms of protein.

Plot 3

Protein Consumption Over Time

This line plot shows the amount of protein I consumed each day. While there were fluctuations, I noticed an upward trend in my protein intake, particularly after I became more conscious of meal prep and ingredients. This is also because of the time gap between observations so was useful for me to see.

Summary

From this analysis, I learned that:

Cooking my meals generally led to better fruit and vegetable intake.

Savoury meals are higher in protein than sweet ones.

My protein intake increased over time as I became more aware of my nutrition.

Tracking my meals helped me make more intentional food choices, and Im excited to continue using this awareness to guide healthier habits. In particular I will have more savoury meals, and continue to prepare most of my meals at home.
